\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Illustration of the metabolic transformation pipeline using fertilizer as an example. Applied fertilizer is treated as a finite impulse, while absorbed fertilizer is modeled by convolving the applied signal with a Gaussian FIR kernel. Panel 1 shows how larger temporal spreads, which define the kernel, result in slower absorption. Panel 2 shows the cumulative fertilizer absorbed over time. Panel 3 shows the fertilizer anomaly, which compares the actual cumulative fertilizer absorbed to the expected level. Panel 4 shows how EMA filtering smooths the effects of cumulative anomalies. Panel 5 shows the nutrient factors that result from the preceding transformations.}}{12}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:metabolism-transformations}{{2}{12}{Illustration of the metabolic transformation pipeline using fertilizer as an example. Applied fertilizer is treated as a finite impulse, while absorbed fertilizer is modeled by convolving the applied signal with a Gaussian FIR kernel. Panel 1 shows how larger temporal spreads, which define the kernel, result in slower absorption. Panel 2 shows the cumulative fertilizer absorbed over time. Panel 3 shows the fertilizer anomaly, which compares the actual cumulative fertilizer absorbed to the expected level. Panel 4 shows how EMA filtering smooths the effects of cumulative anomalies. Panel 5 shows the nutrient factors that result from the preceding transformations}{figure.2}{}}
